    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cross-lingual AI refers to systems where the input and output languages differ, or where a model trained in one language generalizes to others without per-language training. The two most important applications are cross-lingual retrieval (a French query retrieves English documents) and zero-shot cross-lingual transfer (a model fine-tuned on English text classifies Spanish sentences). Modern multilingual embedding models make both practical by mapping all languages into a shared semantic vector space."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Cross-lingual RAG pipeline: user queries in FR/DE/JA/AR flow through language detection into a cross-lingual embedding model (multilingual-e5, LaBSE) that maps all languages to a shared semantic space, enabling retrieval from a monolingual or multilingual knowledge base, with LLM generation responding in the user's original language. Bottom compares translate-first vs native cross-lingual embedding and zero-shot transfer."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Cross-Lingual Embeddings"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A cross-lingual (or multilingual) embedding model maps text from different languages into the same vector space, so that semantically equivalent sentences cluster together regardless of language. The sentence \"How does billing work?\" in English, French, German, and Japanese will all produce vectors that are close to each other in cosine distance. This makes it possible to embed an English knowledge base and retrieve from it using a French query without any translation."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Three strong embedding models for cross-lingual use:"
          }
        ]
